# 🚀 M5 — 2D Landing Simulation

## Overview
M5 extends the system from 1D vertical landing to full 2D planar motion with thrust vectoring, enabling controlled horizontal positioning and precision landing.

---

## System Capabilities

### Dynamics
- 2D motion (x, h)
- Velocity tracking (vx, vh)
- Thrust vectoring via tilt (θ)
- Mass variation due to fuel consumption

### Physics Modeling
- Gravity-based motion
- Engine thrust limits and noise
- Fuel burn affecting mass
- Landing gear spring-damper model

---

## Control System

### Horizontal Control
- Position + velocity feedback
- Tilt-based acceleration control

### Vertical Control
- Velocity tracking with staged descent
- Smooth touchdown targeting (~ -0.3 m/s)

### Constraints
- Tilt angle limits
- Acceleration bounding
- Thrust saturation

---

## Robustness Features

The system is validated under:
- Sensor noise
- Wind disturbances
- Thrust variation
- Random external perturbations

---

## Validation

### Monte Carlo Testing
- 30–50 randomized runs
- Success rate: ~100%

### Performance Metrics
- Peak g-load: ~3.1 – 3.4 g
- Fuel usage: ~0.20 – 0.23 kg
- Landing accuracy: < 1 m
- Touchdown velocity: < 0.1 m/s

---

## Success Criteria

A landing is considered successful if:

- |x| < 1.0 m
- |vx| < 0.1 m/s
- |vh| < 0.1 m/s
- Final height ≤ 0
- Peak g-load < 5 g

---

## Conclusion

M5 demonstrates a robust and stable autonomous landing system in 2D space, capable of handling uncertainty and disturbances while maintaining precise and safe touchdown behavior.

This forms the foundation for future guidance and trajectory planning systems (M6).